      "output": "Title: Question - How to fix this \"WHEA UNCORRECTABLE ERROR\" ? | Tom's Hardware Forum\nURL: https://forums.tomshardware.com/threads/how-to-fix-this-whea-uncorrectable-error.3849072/\nPublished: 2024-07-11T04:51:22.000Z\nAuthor: N/A\nHighlights:\nWelcome to the forums, newcomer! Open up Device Manager and see if there are any items flagged with a yellow exclamation mark.\n\n---\n\nTitle: Fix WHEA_UNCORRECTABLE_ERROR on Windows 11\nURL: https://fixwithtech.com/windows/whea-uncorrectable-error-windows-fix\nPublished: 2026-03-18T12:26:26.000Z\nAuthor: N/A\nHighlights:\nWHEA_UNCORRECTABLE_ERROR in Windows 11 is a hardware-related crash typically caused by CPU, RAM, or motherboard issues.\n...\nThe WHEA_UNCORRECTABLE_ERROR Blue Screen is widely considered one of the most serious system crashes in Windows 11 because it almost always points to hardware-level instability rather than simple software issues. Unlike common blue screen errors triggered by driver conflicts or corrupted system files, this error indicates that the operating system has received a fatal error signal directly from the hardware layer, most commonly from the CPU.\n...\nThe CPU is\n...\n### RAM Instability\n...\nRAM issues are one of the most underestimated causes of WHEA errors. Memory instability can silently corrupt data before the system detects a fatal error.\n...\nTypical causes include:\n...\n- Unstable XMP profiles\n- Mixing different RAM kits\n- Incorrect timings or voltage\n- Faulty memory modules\n...\n### BIOS and Firmware Issues\n...\n- Using outdated CPU microcode\n- Mismanaging memory compatibility\n- Applying incorrect voltage levels\n...\n## Basic Fixes\n...\n### 2. Update Windows\n...\n### 3. Update Drivers\n...\n### 4. Repair System Files\n...\n### 5. Disable Overclocking\n...\nReset all performance tweaks:\n...\n- Disable XMP\n- Remove CPU overclock\n- Restore BIOS defaults\n...\n## Advanced Fixes\n...\n### 2. Update BIOS / UEFI\n...\nUpdating BIOS can resolve:\n...\n- CPU microcode issues\n- Memory compatibility problems\n...\n### 3. Reset BIOS Settings\n...\n### 4. Clean Install Windows\n...\n## Hardware Checks\n...\n### 1. Test RAM Thoroughly\n...\nUse MemTest86:\n...\n### 2. Stress Test CPU\n...\n### 4\n...\nCheck Storage Health\n...\n### 5. Reseat Hardware\n...\n- RAM\n- GPU\n- Power cables\n...\n### 7. Motherboard Issues\n...\nIf all else fails, the motherboard may be the cause.\n...\nThe WHEA_UNCORRECTABLE_ERROR Blue Screen in Windows 11 is a serious indicator of hardware instability that should never be ignored.\n...\nIn most cases, the root cause is:\n...\n- CPU instability\n- RAM issues\n- Storage failure\n- Power delivery problems\n\n---\n\nTitle: Solved: Re: BSOD WHEA_UNCORRECTABLE_ERROR GenuineIntel.sys - Intel Community\nURL: https://community.intel.com/t5/Mobile-and-Desktop-Processors/BSOD-WHEA-UNCORRECTABLE-ERROR-GenuineIntel-sys/m-p/1639751\nPublished: 2024-10-11T15:27:48.000Z\nAuthor: N/A\nHighlights:\noccurring, I\n...\ncomputer and it's\n...\noutput audio device\" and\n...\nturns off fully\n...\nI tried to run\n...\nerrpkt for ffff978983912028, but it gave me the error, \"Unable to locate symbol for nt!WHEA_ERROR_PACKET.\"\n...\nError         : DCACHEL2_DRD_ERR (Proc 1 Bank 11)\n  Status      : 0xfe00000000801136\n  Address\n...\n0x000000008b800000\n  Misc.       : 0x00000430e4000086\n...\nI asked my husband to switch the DIMM to the A slot, which he did. He also cleaned it and inspected it for problems while he was in there. When he plugged it in and turned it back on, the sound reappeared, it did not BSOD, it shutdown normally and was able to wake back up normally after sleeping the computer.\n...\nHe is looking into getting a matching par of DIMMs for both memory channels, thank you for the suggestion.\n...\nThe Intel Processor Diagnostic Tool passed.\n...\nShould I still run the MemTest86? Could I still have memory issues despite the symptoms resolving?\n...\nThis error usually points to the failure being in the processor, but this could also occur as a result of bad memory. The fact that it occurs on the initial boot but then works fine on subsequent boots/reboots points to a failure makes me conclude that this failure has a temperature component (i.e. failing during the cold boot but not after it has had a chance to warm up a bit).\n...\n1. I noticed that you have a single DIMM in Channel B. I suggest that you (while powered down!) move this DIMM to Channel A and see if this makes a difference.\n2. Download and run the Intel Processor Diagnostic Tool. If it fails, attach the detailed report file to your response post.\n...\n3. Download and run MemTest86. I like to see it be run for 12-24 hours; the longer the better. If it fails, attach the details to your response post.\n...\nP.S. You would garner a better performing system if you had a matching pair of DIMMs installed in both memory channels. This allows the processor to interleave accesses and improve memory throughput.\n...\nto switch the DIMM to the A slot, which he did. He also cleaned it and inspected it\n...\nplugged it in and turned it back on, the sound reappeared\n...\nit did not BSOD\n...\nit shutdown normally and was\n...\nto wake back\n...\nafter sleeping the computer\n...\nHe is looking into getting a matching par of DIMMs for both memory channels, thank you for the suggestion.\n...\nThe Intel Processor Diagnostic Tool passed.\n...\nShould I still run the MemTest86? Could I still have memory issues despite the symptoms resolving?\n...\nThat's up to you. Running MemTest86 may not identify any issues, but it should let you know whether the SODIMM is borderline bad.\n\n---\n\nTitle: WHEA uncorrectable errors... - Intel Community\nURL: https://community.intel.com/t5/Mobile-and-Desktop-Processors/WHEA-uncorrectable-errors/td-p/1564951\nPublished: 2024-01-22T10:20:31.000Z\nAuthor: N/A\nHighlights:\nReboot the system and enter BIOS settings, set the BIOS to its default settings, and reboot the system. · Remove any hardware or drivers that ...\n\n---\n\nTitle: Fix WHEA_UNCORRECTABLE_ERROR on Windows 11 | RebootDoctor\nURL: https://rebootdoctor.com/blog/whea-uncorrectable-error-windows-11/\nPublished: 2026-05-27T00:00:00.000Z\nAuthor: N/A\nHighlights:\nShort answer: WHEA_UNCORRECTABLE_ERROR (0x00000124) is one of the few BSODs that genuinely means hardware — the CPU reported an error it could not self-correct. Check Event Viewer under WHEA-Logger for the source. Common culprits are unstable overclocks or XMP/EXPO memory profiles (disable them first), an overheating CPU, a failing PSU, or on Intel 13th/14th-gen chips the known voltage degradation.\n...\nIf you’re overclocking — CPU, RAM with XMP/EXPO, GPU — this is the crash that tells you to stop. An unstable overclock is the single most common trigger for WHEA errors on otherwise healthy hardware. The CPU is running at a voltage or frequency it can’t reliably sustain, and the error correction catches it.\n...\nDisable XMP in BIOS first. If the crashes stop, XMP was pushing the memory controller past what your particular CPU can handle. Try the default 2133 MHz (DDR4) or 4800 MHz (DDR5) for a week. If stable, re-enable XMP at a lower speed — step down one tier at a time until you find what’s stable.\n...\nIf you’\n...\nyou haven’\n...\nanything, check whether your\n...\n’s “auto\n...\n” feature is enabled — many boards ship with something like ASUS’s “AI Overclock Tuner” or MSI’s “Game Boost” turned on by default, pushing the CPU beyond Intel or AMD’s spec without telling you. Disable it.\n...\nPCIe: “Bus/Interconnect Error\n...\nin Event Viewer. Could be a GPU not seated properly, an NVMe SSD with a bad connection, or a dying motherboard PCIe slot. Reseat the\n...\nfirst — pull it\n...\nwith isopropyl alcohol\n...\nyour board has\n...\nInstall HWiNFO and check if thermal throttling or abnormal voltages precede the crashes. CPU hitting 100°C? The overheating is the real problem and WHEA is the symptom. VCore fluctuating wildly under load? PSU or VRM issue.\n...\nAlmost always. The most common exception is an unstable overclock — XMP memory profiles, CPU overclocks, or motherboard auto-overclock features pushing components past their stable limit. Reset everything to stock first. If WHEA errors continue at stock settings with no overclocking, it's genuine hardware failure.\n...\nYes. XMP pushes the memory controller beyond Intel or AMD's official specification. Some CPUs handle it, some can't. Disable XMP in BIOS and run at default speeds for a week. If crashes stop, your CPU's memory controller can't sustain the XMP profile — try re-enabling at a lower speed.\n...\nOpen Event Viewer, Windows Logs, System, filter for WHEA-Logger events. The Error Source field tells you: Machine Check Exception means CPU. PCIe Bus Error means GPU, NVMe, or slot issue. If the same CPU core is named in every crash, the CPU die has a defect — contact the manufacturer for warranty replacement.",
